09/06/2010
ANKARA, Turkey -- Russia and Turkey signed a nuclear co-operation deal Tuesday (June 8th), on the sidelines of the Conference on Interaction and Confidence-Building Measures in Asia.
Under the deal, the two countries will exchange information and know-how in the licensing of nuclear facilities and activities.
Speaking at a joint press conference after the signing ceremony, Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan said Ankara will make relations with Moscow a foreign policy priority.
Russian counterpart Vladimir Putin outlined Moscow's wish to develop projects to boost Russian natural gas exports, via Turkey.
(Zaman - 09/06/10;
AFP, Xinhua - 08/06/10)
